Hi Ben and welcome,

That’s a good question.  Uber is a ride-sharing service that operates in many cities, but perhaps not in yours.  Instead of hailing a traditional cab, riders use an app on their phone to request a trip.  A driver for this service then uses GPS to locate and pick up that rider.  Here’s something to wonder—why would such an app be preferable to hailing a traditional cab?  Additionally, what does this graph tell you about the relationship between the number of miles a driver spends cruising for requests and the number of trip requests?

